	<h3>Cancer Screen (Endoscopic Studies) Panel</h3>

<ul class="bullet3">
<li>Endoscopy</li>
<ul class="bullet2"><li>Endoscopy utilizes a thin, flexible, lighted tube with an optical camera to visually examine the inside of body. It is more accurate than x-ray for detecting inflammation or small lesions such as ulcers or tumors within the reach of the instrument. Its other major advantage over x-ray is the ability to perform biopsies (obtain small pieces of tissue) or cytology (obtain some cells with a fine brush) for microscopic examination to determine its nature and whether the lesion is benign or malignant (cancerous). <br><br>Biopsies are taken for many reasons and may not mean that cancer is suspected. Patients who are over 50 years old or those who are at higher-than-average risk of having colorectal cancer are strongly advised to undergo colorectal cancer screening. This test is, however, is more invasive that x-ray studies and there is good evidence that endoscopic screening would result in rare but serious side effects associated with the procedure. They include perforation, cardiopulmonary events, aspiration pneumonia, and bleeding requiring hospitalization.</li>
</ul></ul><br>

<ul class="bullet3">
<li>Gastroscopy</li>
<ul class="bullet2"><li>It is basically an examination of the stomach but the esophagus is also examined during the procedure. A gastroscope is passed through the mouth and esophagus to the stomach. The patient's throat is sprayed with a local anesthetic to reduce discomfort and gagging. Patients may also receive medicine to relax them. Through the gastroscope which is connected to a TV monitor, the doctor can look directly at the inside of the stomach. If an abnormal area is found, then the doctor can and will remove some tissue (a biopsy). Another doctor, a pathologist, examines the tissue under a microscope to check for cancer cells.</li>
</ul></ul><br>

<ul class="bullet3">
<li>Colonoscopy</li>
<ul class="bullet2"><li>It is similar to gastroscopy but this time it examines the entire colon and rectum. This is accomplished by inserting the tube that is about the thickness of a finger into the anus, and then advancing it slowly, under visual control, into the rectum and through the colon. It is performed with the visual control of either looking through the instrument or with viewing a TV monitor. Colonoscopic examination is a more sensitive method of surveillance than double contrast
barium enema.</li>
</ul></ul><br>



